This began shortly after Jeremy became a leader, while the colleagues I worked for before thought they shared similar political views began to expect me to make a reversal and take positions I would never agree with – be it on national security or the EU single market.
Whenever I make public statements – no matter what I say – there is a whole offensive tirade on social media calling for withdrawal, rejection of moderate politics, statements that I do not belong to Labour.
Like this doesn't just happen to me.
In fact, I know that I have even been more fortunate than some of my colleagues, since the comments about me are at least primarily political in nature.
I can only admire the professionalism and dedication of those colleagues who face sexist or racist upheavals every day without fear of them.
One of the biggest disappointments of this era in politics is how such insults became the norm.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said Labour should embrace a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that the party is far from wide-ranging, with every sign of mistrust or change in the rules of the election becoming increasingly narrow-minded.
Over the past two years, I have received a lot of advice to calm down, not to talk so much and that then "everything will be fine".
But that's not why I went into politics.
Ever since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student provoked by the Thatcher government, which through my neglect led to the literal collapse of my excellent school, I have fought for better public services for those who need them most – whether as a local councilor or as a minister.
I have never hid my political views, including during the last elections.
No one in Nottingham East could be confused in any way by my political position and my disagreement with the current leadership.
To all those who supported Friday's proposal, I would like to say that when the state rushes to Brexit, it will hurt households, businesses and the public sector, and I do not understand the desire to waste my time and energy in loyalty to the Labour leader.
But my real message is not to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are Labour members or not: It is my pride to serve you and I promise that no threat of revocation or political excommunication will deny me the way I consider best in protecting your interests.
Chrissy Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East.
