John Edwards: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a reputation for academic excellence, continuing in 2018 with another superior performance of exam scores, which is only reinforced by individual and collective success in sports disciplines, art, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Association of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best level to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education, their chosen career and their place in a global world.
As an educational sector that can compose and implement a personalized curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to someone in a language they can understand, your words get to them.
But if you speak in his own language, you touch his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on the English language when we want to build relationships and trust with the peoples of other countries.
Through the results of this year’s exams, we see that languages are first and foremost with the highest success for independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high A score.
The data, collected by 74 members of SCIS schools, showed that 72% of students achieved an A score in Chinese, with the same score having 72% of German learners, 69% of French learners and 63% of those with Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland perceive foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Currently, languages as a subject of free choice by students receive the same attitude as natural-mathematical disciplines (scientific, technological, engineering and mathematical disciplines) both in the programs of independent schools and beyond.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission showed that 17% of employers found insufficient language skills to make it difficult for them to find employees.
Therefore, more and more foreign language proficiency is becoming mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more jobs require foreign language proficiency, which makes these skills essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if a person masters a foreign language, he will have a real advantage in the future, having mastered such a skill, which remains for life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts the multilingual person one breast ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to speak a language, with French being the only language whose proficiency reached a two-digit rate of 15%.
That is why investing in language learning today is important for children now.
Proficiency in several languages, especially those of emerging economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, every school will be different from the languages taught.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered more important to the UK in the future by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever interests your child may have, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers being specialists in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are determined to provide an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the necessary skills to succeed in life, no matter what the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages continue to play an incredibly important role for the future of any country, which requires this to be taken into account in the education system.
Indeed, modern languages should be realistically considered “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellent quality, to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Association of Independent Schools.
