North Korea Says 'No Way' to Disarm Unilaterally, Without Confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions deepened distrust of the United States and there was no way the country could unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
At the annual General Assembly of the World Organization, Ri Yong-hou said that "significant goodwill measures" had been taken over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, destroying the nuclear test site, and vowing not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we will not believe in our own national security, and under no circumstances will we be able to disarm unilaterally first.”
While Ri voiced North Korea’s familiar grievances about Washington’s resistance to a “step-by-step” approach to eliminating nuclear weapons, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking step-by-step measures, his statement seemed significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri cited a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work for “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump gave guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls for easing tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists 'first to remove nuclear weapons' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through coercion, and even objects to the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can make us fall to our knees is a meaningless dream for those who don’t know us.
The problem, however, is that the ongoing sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention whether a second meeting between Kim and Trump was planned, which the U.S. leader stressed through the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister stressed on the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the country on the issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea and not the United States, the removal of nuclear weapons on the Korean Peninsula would not have reached such a stagnation.
However, Ri’s tone of speech was significantly different from the previous year when he told the U.N. General Assembly that directing North Korean missiles to the continental United States was inevitable after “evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
That year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened North Korea with “total destruction” last year, praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea removes its nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no deadline and said, “It doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that "implementation of Security Council sanctions must necessarily continue until complete, definitive and confirmed nuclear disarmament takes place."
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in a bid to halt funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
This year, Pompeo visited North Korea three times, but his last trip went well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, but only hours later North Korea accused him of making "gangster demands".
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea promised to destroy a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States takes “appropriate measures.”
According to him, Kim told him that the “relevant measures” he was seeking were the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and that he wanted to achieve a normalization of relations with Washington.
Students at Harvard on a course for enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year makes all students sleep more in an attempt to combat the growing culture of “all-night learning” using caffeine.
A lecturer found that students at the world’s number one university often don’t even think about the very foundations of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Kaysler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women’s Hospital, has prepared a course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“Finally a girl came to me and said, ‘Why do they tell me this now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being held for the first time this year, explains to students the most important things about how good sleep habits help academic and athletic achievement, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Bareira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after it was found that students suffered from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is an image of a dorm room where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to explain the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of bedtime sleep routine.
Another part of the participants told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Then a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke.”
The culture of pride in “learning all night” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring adequate and quality sleep should be the “secret weapon” for students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he says – even to avoid weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in a hunger mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Kaysler prepare the course by taking one of his classes during his first year at Harvard.
He says his course “opened his eyes” and inspired him to spread it throughout the campus.
It hopes that the next step is for all graduates to be asked to complete a similar curriculum before joining a competitive institution.
Professor Kaysler recommends that students consider setting up a bedtime and wake-up alarm and being aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted from electronic screens and LED lighting, which can upset the circadian rhythm and lead to problems with falling asleep.
