World Wide Web inventor Tim Berners-Lee is launching a venture that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that is building the Berners-Lee Solid open source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people have permission to access certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intent behind Inrupt was “world domination.”
“We have to do it now,” he said with regard to the undertaking.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid technology, which allows people to create their own "online personal data repository" or POD.
It contains lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It looks like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, which are available through any browser, and at the same time it is all at the same time.
The unique thing about the online personal data repository is that the user determines who has access to what information.
The company calls it “granting authority for personal data.”
The idea behind Inrupt, according to company CEO John Bruce, is for the company to invest resources, processes and appropriate skills to help Solid become accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers contracted to work on the project, and a group of volunteer programmers.
As of this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether to make a complete change or not when all of their business models are completely updated overnight.
“We don’t ask permission from them.”
In a post in Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s mission is to provide energy for trade and ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid.
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has had a strong influence in the net neutrality debate.
Despite launching Inrupt, Burners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely optimistic about this new era on the internet,” Berners-Lee added.
