The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
A new study, carried out at a mansion in the Scottish mountains, aims to find out how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation actions.
The study by scientists from the National Trust of Scotland will follow the common bats, as well as brown-eared water-nostrils at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations in the mansion to track bat activities during the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of call sounds of bats, as well as which species issue them.
A habitat map and report will then be drawn up to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation adviser, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. meadow creation, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK as a whole have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to habitat loss.
Populations may be at risk from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical treatment of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, due to their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation techniques to detect insects and obstacles along their flight trajectory.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of great importance and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts who conduct regular surveys, shelter inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even established the first and only special bat reserve in the Three Mansion in the Dumfries and Galway area, which is home to eight of the ten bat species in Scotland.
The manor manager, David Thompson, says it's the perfect territory for them.
“Here at Threeve, we have great bat terrain,” he said.
“We have old buildings, many old trees and a suitable habitat.
But there are many more things about bats that are not known, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stressed that it is important to check for the presence of bats before property maintenance activities are carried out, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of one shelter would kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as destroy an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their shelters.
Elizabeth Farrell, a Scottish employee at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, "I still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our animal species, because we just don't know what happens to their populations."
