The 42-year-old has accepted the challenge to revive the club from northeast England, which is currently in third position in the Premier League, three points from the first place.
He moved to the Stadium of Light this summer after taking St. Mirren back to the Scottish Premier League last season.
“I wanted to play for my country as a player.
I recorded one game for the B team and that was it,” Ross told BBC Sportsound.
“But I grew up with the Scottish Hampden games, which my father and I watched as a child, so the national team has always attracted me.
“But this opportunity would only open up if I had success at the club level.”
Ross' predecessors as Sunderland managers included Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet, and Paolo Di Canio.
Aloe Athletic's former mentor said he was not worried about being the successor to such established names at such a famous club, having previously rejected offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
“For me, success will now be measured by a positive answer to the question ‘Can I bring this club back to the Premier League?’
Because in structure, base and conditions he is undoubtedly at the level of the Premier League," he said.
“It won’t be easy to get back to the highest level of football, but I will accept that I have achieved success here only if I can bring the team back there.”
Ross has only been a manager for three years after spending some time as an assistant at Dumbarton and 15 months at Harts' coaching staff.
He then helped Aloe avoid falling into the Third Division and turned St. Mirren from a relegated team into a Champions League winner the following season.
Ross says he now feels more comfortable than during his career as a footballer in Clyde, Hartlepool, Folkerk, St. Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"I was really at a crossroads," he remembers the time he took Aloe.
“I really believed that being a manager was the best field for me, including being an active player.
It sounds strange because I did well, I made good money, and I had some significant successes.
But being a player is sometimes hard.
There are a lot of things you have to deal with every week.
I’m still facing the same levels of stress and strain at work, but I just feel that being a manager is the right direction for me.
I’ve always wanted to be a manager, and now that I’m really doing it, I’ve never felt more comfortable in my skin in my entire conscious life.”
