Here are some basic facts about Palu and Dongala, which are located on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the province of central Sulawesi, located at the end of a narrow beach on the west coast of the island of Sulawesi, with a population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city celebrated its 40th anniversary when an earthquake and tsunami struck.
Dongala is a regency that stretches over 300 km (180 mi) along the coastline of Sulawesi Island.
The regency, which is an administrative region smaller than a province, had an estimated population of 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and farming are the foundations of the economy of the province of central Sulawesi, especially in the coastal region of Dongala.
Nickel mining is also important for the province, but it is concentrated mainly in Morovali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Dongala have been hit several times by tsunamis over the past 100 years, according to data from the Indonesian Disaster Recovery Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of buildings in Dongala.
The tsunami struck the western part of Dongala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismic "Pacific Ring of Fire" and is regularly mown by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A severe earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in North Sumatra triggered a tsunami that struck 14 countries and killed 226,000 people along the entire coastline of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake mows Indonesia’s most populous island, Java, triggering a tsunami that crashed in the south coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A magnitude 7.6 earthquake strikes near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake decimated one of the Mentawai Islands and triggered a 10-metre tsunami wave that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake struck the Paddy Jaya Regency in Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people remembered the devastation of the deadly earthquake and tsunami in 2004.
This time, no tsunami was triggered, but more than 100 people were killed by collapsed buildings.
2018: Strong earthquakes rocked the tourist island of Lombok in Indonesia, killing more than 500 people, most of them on the northern side of the island.
