New to the Red Tide: Concentrations Decrease in Pinelas, Manitoba and Sarasota
The latest report of the Florida Committee on Fish and Wildlife shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in sections of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Committee, there are reports of conditions for undergrowth in the areas of Pinellas, Mantua, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – this indicates a decrease in concentrations.
Excessive red tide water stretches approximately 130 miles along the coast, from the northern Pinelas County to the southern Lee County.
Areas with algae can be seen 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but are smaller compared to last week.
A red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
During the past week, there have been reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal zone or slightly further inland in the county of Pinellas, low to high concentrations along the coast of Hillsborough County, preconditions for high concentrations in Manuthi County, preconditions for high concentrations in the coast or further inland in Sarasota County, precincts in the county of Pinelas County, and low to high concentrations along the coast of Hillsborough County.
Inflammation of the respiratory tract continues to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manuti, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There have been no reports of respiratory infections in Northwest Florida in the past week.
